Sure! Below is an example of a simple HTML web app that displays a random sentence from a hypothetical source (since I can't fetch data from that URL directly) and colors each word in the sentence in rainbow colors. You can copy and paste this code into an HTML file, and it should work as intended.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Rainbow Random Sentence</title>
    <style>
        body {
            display: flex;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            height: 100vh;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }
        .rainbow {
            font-size: 2em;
            display: flex;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<div id="sentence" class="rainbow"></div>

<script>
    // Example sentences simulating content from the mentioned URL
    const sentences = [
        "I told my computer I needed a break, and now it won't stop sending me beach wallpapers.",
        "Why did the scarecrow win an award? Because he was outstanding in his field.",
        "I used to play piano by ear, but now I use my hands.",
        "The mathematician's plants stopped growing because they kept taking root.",
        "I'm reading a book on anti-gravity. It's impossible to put down."
    ];

    // Function to generate a random sentence
    function getRandomSentence() {
        const randomIndex = Math.floor(Math.random() * sentences.length);
        return sentences[randomIndex];
    }

    // Function to color each word in rainbow colors
    function displayRainbowSentence(sentence) {
        const colors = ['#FF0000', '#FF7F00', '#FFFF00', '#7FFF00', '#00FF00', '#00FF7F', '#00FFFF', '#007FFF', '#0000FF', '#7F00FF', '#FF00FF', '#FF007F'];
        const words = sentence.split(' ');
        const rainbowSentence = words.map((word, index) => {
            const color = colors[index % colors.length];
            return `<span style="color: ${color};">${word}</span>`;
        }).join(' ');

        document.getElementById('sentence').innerHTML = rainbowSentence;
    }

    // Display a random rainbow sentence on load
    displayRainbowSentence(getRandomSentence());
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

You can run this code in your local development environment by saving it in an `.html` file and opening it in a web browser. Each time you refresh the page, you'll see a different sentence displayed in rainbow colors!
